I too succeeded in gaining a place at a top selective school and I can only say that what I was taught by my parents was far more instrumental in my success than what the National Curriculum had to offer. &#10;One thing concerns me though - do you not worry about the potential effect on your boys' social skills? And is there anything you did to attempt to compensate for their reduced exposure to peer groups? I've often thought that learning to deal with social situations (particularly involving the opposite sex...!) are just as crucial a part of school as what is taught in lessons. Is this something you were able to compensate for in any way? "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="950" language="en" documentId="715" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="sithepi" date="07 January 2011 10:50am" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/9049378" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="18" thumbsDown="0" origId="715" notes="" title="Why I home school my children"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="7"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="8" end="508"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="509" end="950"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47"/></xmi:XMI>